Author: Dicklesworthstone <jeff141421@gmail.com>
Date:   Thu May 7 09:16:37 2026 -0400

    perf(direct-dml): cache hinted leaf for repeated fixed-width UPDATEs

    Adds a `PreparedDirectDmlLeafHint` (root_page + leaf_page) on Connection
    that caches the leaf page whose payload was just overwritten in place by
    a fixed-width same-size direct-simple UPDATE. On the next direct-simple
    UPDATE against the same root, the connection probes that leaf first via
    the new `BtCursor::table_move_to_leaf_hint`, which walks from root only
    if the hinted page is no longer a table leaf or its [min,max] rowid
    bounds no longer contain the target rowid. This cuts the tight UPDATE
    loop's seek cost from a full root descent to a single leaf-page load
    when subsequent UPDATEs land on the same leaf — the common case for
    batch UPDATEs over a small key window.

    Hint lifecycle (kept conservative to avoid stale-page reads):

    - Stored only after a successful in-place same-size payload overwrite,
      and only while we are inside an open transaction (writes outside a
      transaction can race with checkpoint moves).
    - Stored only for the `fixed_width_real_assignment` direct-simple
      UPDATE path; mixed-shape and overflow-rewriting paths clear it.
    - Cleared on direct-simple INSERT execution, on direct-simple UPDATE
      paths that fall through to delete+insert, on the direct-insert
      append-hint reset, and whenever the same-size in-place overwrite
      fails. The cleanup also runs alongside
      `clear_prepared_direct_insert_append_hint` so the two prepared-path
      hints can never disagree about cursor position.

    `table_move_to_leaf_hint` returns Ok(None) (so callers fall back to
    root descent) when the hinted page is no longer a table leaf or the
    target rowid is outside the leaf's bounds, and otherwise positions the
    cursor exactly as `table_move_to` would: Found leaves cell_idx on the
    match, NotFound clamps to the successor cell within the leaf, the
    table_seek memo is refreshed, and a `WitnessKey::Cell` point witness
    is recorded so subsequent point reads can short-circuit.

    Test coverage: `test_table_move_to_leaf_hint_uses_hinted_leaf_when_bounds_match`
    covers the three branches — exact match (Found), not-found-but-inside
    (NotFound with successor positioning), and bounds-miss (None fallback).

